# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autoregressive-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In time series analysis used in statistics and econometrics, **autoregressive integrated moving average** (**ARIMA**) and **seasonal ARIMA** (**SARIMA**) models are generalizations of the autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model to non-stationary series and periodic variation, respectively.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] All these models are fitted to time series in order to better understand it and predict future values.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The purpose of these generalizations is to fit the data as well as possible.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, ARMA assumes that the series is stationary, that is, its expected value is constant in time.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If instead the series has a trend (but a constant variance/autocovariance), the trend is removed by "differencing", leaving a stationary series.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This operation generalizes ARMA and corresponds to the "integrated" part of ARIMA.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Analogously, periodic variation is removed by "seasonal differencing".
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] As in ARMA, the "autoregressive" (AR) part of ARIMA indicates that the evolving variable of interest is regressed on its prior values.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "moving average" (MA) part indicates that the regression error is a linear combination of error terms whose values occurred contemporaneously and at various times in the past.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "integrated" (I) part indicates that the data values have been replaced with the difference between each value and the previous value.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] According to Wold's decomposition theorem the ARMA model is sufficient to describe a **regular** (a.k.a. purely nondeterministic) wide-sense stationary time series.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This motivates to make such a non-stationary time series stationary, e.g., by using differencing, before using ARMA.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time series contains a **predictable** sub-process (a.k.a. pure sine or complex-valued exponential process), the predictable component is treated as a non-zero-mean but periodic (i.e., seasonal) component in the ARIMA framework that it is eliminated by the seasonal differencing.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal ARIMA models are usually denoted by ARIMA(*p*, *d*, *q*)(*P*, *D*, *Q*)*m*, where the uppercase *P*, *D*, *Q* are the autoregressive, differencing, and moving average terms for the seasonal part of the ARIMA model, and *m* is the number of periods in each season.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] When two of the parameters are 0, the model may be referred to based on the non-zero parameter, dropping "AR", "I" or "MA" from the acronym.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where L is the lag operator, the $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters of the autoregressive part of the model, the $\theta _{i}$ are the parameters of the moving average part and the $\varepsilon _{t}$ are error terms.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The error terms $\varepsilon _{t}$ are generally assumed to be independent, identically distributed variables sampled from a normal distribution with zero mean.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] and so is special case of an ARMA(*p+d*, *q*) process having the autoregressive polynomial with *d* unit roots.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The above can be generalized as follows.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The explicit identification of the factorization of the autoregression polynomial into factors as above can be extended to other cases, firstly to apply to the moving average polynomial and secondly to include other special factors.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For example, having a factor $(1-L^{s})$ in a model is one way of including a non-stationary seasonality of period *s* into the model; this factor has the effect of re-expressing the data as changes from *s* periods ago.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Another example is the factor $\left(1-{\sqrt {3}}L+L^{2}\right)$ , which includes a (non-stationary) seasonality of period 2.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The effect of the first type of factor is to allow each season's value to drift separately over time, whereas with the second type values for adjacent seasons move together.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A stationary time series's properties do not change.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, for a wide-sense stationary time series, the mean and the variance/autocovariance are constant over time.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] **Differencing** in statistics is a transformation applied to a non-stationary time-series in order to make it trend stationary (i.e., stationary *in the mean sense*), by removing or subtracting the trend or non-constant mean.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] However, it does not affect the non-stationarity of the variance or autocovariance.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Likewise, *seasonal differencing* or *deseasonalization* is applied to a time-series to remove the seasonal component.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] From the perspective of signal processing, especially the Fourier spectral analysis theory, the trend is a low-frequency part in the spectrum of a series, while the season is a periodic-frequency part.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Therefore, differencing is a high-pass (that is, low-stop) filter and the seasonal-differencing is a comb filter to suppress respectively the low-frequency trend and the periodic-frequency season in the spectrum domain (rather than directly in the time domain).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To difference the data, we compute the difference between consecutive observations.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal differencing involves computing the difference between an observation and the corresponding observation in the previous season e.g a year.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The differenced data are then used for the estimation of an ARMA model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Some well-known special cases arise naturally or are mathematically equivalent to other popular forecasting models.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The order *p* and *q* can be determined using the sample autocorrelation function (ACF), partial autocorrelation function (PACF), and/or extended autocorrelation function (EACF) method.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Other alternative methods include AIC, BIC, etc.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To determine the order of a non-seasonal ARIMA model, a useful criterion is the Akaike information criterion (AIC).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where *L*is the likelihood of the data, *p*is the order of the autoregressive part and *q*is the order of the moving average part.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The *k* represents the intercept of the ARIMA model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For AIC, if *k* = 1 then there is an intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*≠ 0) and if *k*= 0 then there is no intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*= 0).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The objective is to minimize the AIC, AICc or BIC values for a good model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The lower the value of one of these criteria for a range of models being investigated, the better the model will suit the data.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The AIC and the BIC are used for two completely different purposes.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] While the AIC tries to approximate models towards the reality of the situation, the BIC attempts to find the perfect fit.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The BIC approach is often criticized as there never is a perfect fit to real-life complex data; however, it is still a useful method for selection as it penalizes models more heavily for having more parameters than the AIC would.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] AICc can only be used to compare ARIMA models with the same orders of differencing.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For ARIMAs with different orders of differencing, RMSE can be used for model comparison.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The ARIMA model can be viewed as a "cascade" of two models.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Now forecasts can be made for the process $Y_{t}$ , using a generalization of the method of autoregressive forecasting.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The forecast intervals (confidence intervals for forecasts) for ARIMA models are based on assumptions that the residuals are uncorrelated and normally distributed.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If either of these assumptions does not hold, then the forecast intervals may be incorrect.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For this reason, researchers plot the ACF and histogram of the residuals to check the assumptions before producing forecast intervals.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For $h=1$ , $v_{T+h\,\mid \,T}={\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ for all ARIMA models regardless of parameters and orders.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In general, forecast intervals from ARIMA models will increase as the forecast horizon increases.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A number of variations on the ARIMA model are commonly employed.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If multiple time series are used then the $X_{t}$ can be thought of as vectors and a VARIMA model may be appropriate.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Sometimes a seasonal effect is suspected in the model; in that case, it is generally considered better to use a SARIMA (seasonal ARIMA) model than to increase the order of the AR or MA parts of the model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time-series is suspected to exhibit long-range dependence, then the *d* parameter may be allowed to have non-integer values in an autoregressive fractionally integrated moving average model, which is also called a Fractional ARIMA (FARIMA or ARFIMA) model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Various packages that apply methodology like Box–Jenkins parameter optimization are available to find the right parameters for the ARIMA model.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:autoregressive-models/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] A **language model** is a computational model that predicts sequences in natural language.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Large language models (LLMs), currently their most advanced form as of 2026, are predominantly based on transformers trained on larger datasets (frequently using texts scraped from the public internet).
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] They have superseded recurrent neural network-based models, which had previously superseded the purely statistical models, such as the word *n*-gram language model.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Noam Chomsky did pioneering work on language models in the 1950s by developing a theory of formal grammars.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] In 1980, statistical approaches were explored and found to be more useful for many purposes than rule-based formal grammars.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Discrete representations like word *n*-gram language models, with probabilities for discrete combinations of words, made significant advances.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] In the 2000s, continuous representations for words, such as word embeddings, began to replace discrete representations.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes a word’s meaning such that words closer in vector space are similar in meaning and common relationships between words, such as plurality or gender, are preserved.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] A word *n*-gram language model is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] If one previous word is considered, it is a bigram model; if two words, a trigram model; if *n* − 1 words, an *n*-gram model.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Special tokens are introduced to denote the start and end of a sentence $\langle s\rangle$ and $\langle /s\rangle$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] To prevent a zero probability being assigned to unseen words, the probability of each seen word is slightly lowered to make room for the unseen words in a given corpus.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] To achieve this, various smoothing methods are used, from simple "add-one" smoothing (assigning a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams, as an uninformative prior) to more sophisticated techniques, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Word *n-*gram models have largely been superseded by recurrent neural network–based models, which in turn have been superseded by Transformer-based models often referred to as large language models.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Maximum entropy language models encode the relationship between a word and the *n*-gram history using feature functions.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] where $Z(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m-1})$ is the partition function, a is the parameter vector, and $f(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m})$ is the feature function.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] In the simplest case, the feature function is just an indicator of the presence of a certain *n*-gram.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] It is helpful to use a prior on a or some form of regularization.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] The log-bilinear model is another example of an exponential language model.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Skip-gram language model is an attempt at overcoming the data sparsity problem that the preceding model (i.e. word *n*-gram language model) faced.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Words represented in an embedding vector were not necessarily consecutive anymore, but could leave gaps that are *skipped* over (thus the name "skip-gram").
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Formally, a k-skip-n-gram is a length-n subsequence where the components occur at distance at most k from each other.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] In skip-gram model, semantic relations between words are represented by linear combinations, capturing a form of compositionality.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] where ≈ is made precise by stipulating that its right-hand side must be the nearest neighbor of the value of the left-hand side.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Continuous representations or embeddings of words are produced in recurrent neural network-based language models (known also as *continuous space language models*).
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Such continuous space embeddings help to alleviate the curse of dimensionality, which is the consequence of the number of possible sequences of words increasing exponentially with the size of the vocabulary, further causing a data sparsity problem.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Neural networks avoid this problem by representing words as non-linear combinations of weights in a neural net.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] A large language model (LLM) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Although sometimes matching human performance, it is not clear whether they are plausible cognitive models.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] At least for recurrent neural networks, it has been shown that they sometimes learn patterns that humans do not, but fail to learn patterns that humans typically do.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Evaluation of the quality of language models is mostly done by comparison to human created sample benchmarks created from typical language-oriented tasks.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Other, less established, quality tests examine the intrinsic character of a language model or compare two such models.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Since language models are typically intended to be dynamic and to learn from data they see, some proposed models investigate the rate of learning, e.g., through inspection of learning curves.
[src:autoregressive-models/language-model] Various data sets have been developed for use in evaluating language processing systems.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In probability theory and statistics, a **Markov chain** or **Markov process** is a stochastic process describing a sequence of possible events in which the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Informally, this may be thought of as, "What happens next depends only on the state of affairs *now*." A countably infinite sequence, in which the chain moves state at discrete time steps, gives a discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time process is called a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes are named in honor of the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov chains have many applications as statistical models of real-world processes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The adjectives *Markovian* and *Markov* are used to describe something that is related to a Markov process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov process is a stochastic process that satisfies the Markov property (sometimes characterized as "memorylessness").
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In simpler terms, it is a process for which predictions can be made regarding future outcomes based solely on its present state and—most importantly—such predictions are just as good as the ones that could be made knowing the process's full history.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, conditional on the present state of the system, its future and past states are independent.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is a type of Markov process that has either a discrete state space or a discrete index set (often representing time), but the precise definition of a Markov chain varies.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The system's state space and time parameter index need to be specified.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Note that there is no definitive agreement in the literature on the use of some of the terms that signify special cases of Markov processes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Usually the term "Markov chain" is reserved for a process with a discrete set of times, that is, a **discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC)**, but a few authors use the term "Markov process" to refer to a **continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC)** without explicit mention.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In addition, there are other extensions of Markov processes that are referred to as such but do not necessarily fall within any of these four categories (see Markov model).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Moreover, the time index need not necessarily be real-valued; like with the state space, there are conceivable processes that move through index sets with other mathematical constructs.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Notice that the general state space continuous-time Markov chain is general to such a degree that it has no designated term.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] While the time parameter is usually discrete, the state space of a Markov chain does not have any generally agreed-on restrictions: the term may refer to a process on an arbitrary state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] However, many applications of Markov chains employ finite or countably infinite state spaces, which have a more straightforward statistical analysis.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Besides time-index and state-space parameters, there are many other variations, extensions and generalizations (see Variations).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] For simplicity, most of this article concentrates on the discrete-time, discrete state-space case, unless mentioned otherwise.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The changes of state of the system are called transitions.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The probabilities associated with various state changes are called transition probabilities.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The process is characterized by a state space, a transition matrix describing the probabilities of particular transitions, and an initial state (or initial distribution) across the state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] By convention, we assume all possible states and transitions have been included in the definition of the process, so there is always a next state, and the process does not terminate.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A discrete-time random process involves a system which is in a certain state at each step, with the state changing randomly between steps.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The steps are often thought of as moments in time, but they can equally well refer to physical distance or any other discrete measurement.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Formally, the steps are the integers or natural numbers, and the random process is a mapping of these to states.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The Markov property states that the conditional probability distribution for the system at the next step (and in fact at all future steps) depends only on the current state of the system, and not additionally on the state of the system at previous steps.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since the system changes randomly, it is generally impossible to predict with certainty the state of a Markov chain at a given point in the future.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] However, the statistical properties of the system's future can be predicted.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In many applications, it is these statistical properties that are important.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Markov studied Markov processes in the early 20th century, publishing his first paper on the topic in 1906.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes in continuous time were discovered long before his work in the early 20th century in the form of the Poisson process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov was interested in studying an extension of independent random sequences, motivated by a disagreement with Pavel Nekrasov who claimed independence was necessary for the weak law of large numbers to hold.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov later used Markov chains to study the distribution of vowels in Eugene Onegin, written by Alexander Pushkin, and proved a central limit theorem for such chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In 1912 Henri Poincaré studied Markov chains on finite groups with an aim to study card shuffling.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Other early uses of Markov chains include a diffusion model, introduced by Paul and Tatyana Ehrenfest in 1907, and a branching process, introduced by Francis Galton and Henry William Watson in 1873, preceding the work of Markov.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] After the work of Galton and Watson, it was later revealed that their branching process had been independently discovered and studied around three decades earlier by Irénée-Jules Bienaymé.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Starting in 1928, Maurice Fréchet became interested in Markov chains, eventually resulting in him publishing in 1938 a detailed study on Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Kolmogorov developed in a 1931 paper a large part of the early theory of continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov was partly inspired by Louis Bachelier's 1900 work on fluctuations in the stock market as well as Norbert Wiener's work on Einstein's model of Brownian movement.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] He introduced and studied a particular set of Markov processes known as diffusion processes, where he derived a set of differential equations describing the processes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Independent of Kolmogorov's work, Sydney Chapman derived in a 1928 paper an equation, now called the Chapman–Kolmogorov equation, in a less mathematically rigorous way than Kolmogorov, while studying Brownian movement.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The differential equations are now called the Kolmogorov equations or the Kolmogorov–Chapman equations.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Other mathematicians who contributed significantly to the foundations of Markov processes include William Feller, starting in 1930s, and then later Eugene Dynkin, starting in the 1950s.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that there is a coin purse containing five coins worth 25¢ (quarters), five coins worth 10¢ (dimes) and five coins worth 5¢ (nickels).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] One by one, coins are randomly drawn from the purse and are set on a table.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If $X_{n}$ represents the total value of the coins set on the table after n draws, with $X_{0}=0$ , then the sequence $\{X_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ is *not* a Markov process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] To see why this is the case, suppose that in the first six draws, all five nickels and a quarter are drawn.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If we know not just $X_{6}$ , but the earlier values as well, then we can determine which coins have been drawn, and we know that the next coin will not be a nickel; so we can determine that $X_{7}\geq \$0.60$ with probability 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] But if we do not know the earlier values, then based only on the value $X_{6}$ we might guess that we had drawn four dimes and two nickels, in which case it would certainly be possible to draw another nickel next.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Thus, our guesses about $X_{7}$ are impacted by our knowledge of values prior to $X_{6}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] However, it is possible to model this scenario as a Markov process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Instead of defining $X_{n}$ to represent the *total value* of the coins on the table, we could define $X_{n}$ to represent the *count* of the various coin types on the table.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] For instance, $X_{6}=1,0,5$ could be defined to represent the state where there is one quarter, zero dimes, and five nickels on the table after 6 one-by-one draws.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This new model could be represented by $6\times 6\times 6=216$ possible states, where each state represents the number of coins of each type (from 0 to 5) that are on the table.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that the first draw results in state $X_{1}=0,1,0$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The probability of achieving $X_{2}$ now depends on $X_{1}$ ; for example, the state $X_{2}=1,0,1$ is not possible.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] After the second draw, the third draw depends on which coins have so far been drawn, but no longer only on the coins that were drawn for the first state (since probabilistically important information has since been added to the scenario).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In this way, the likelihood of the $X_{n}=i,j,k$ state depends exclusively on the outcome of the $X_{n-1}=\ell ,m,p$ state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The possible values of *X**i* form a countable set *S* called the state space of the chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since each row of **P** sums to one and all elements are non-negative, **P** is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] is a normalized ( ${\textstyle \sum _{i}\pi _{i}=1}$ ) multiple of a left eigenvector **e** of the transition matrix **P** with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If there is more than one unit eigenvector then a weighted sum of the corresponding stationary states is also a stationary state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] But for a Markov chain one is usually more interested in a stationary state that is the limit of the sequence of distributions for some initial distribution.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The values of a stationary distribution $\textstyle \pi _{i}$ are associated with the state space of **P** and its eigenvectors have their relative proportions preserved.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since the components of π are positive and the constraint that their sum is unity can be rewritten as ${\textstyle \sum _{i}1\cdot \pi _{i}=1}$ we see that the dot product of π with a vector whose components are all 1 is unity and that π lies on a simplex.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is time-homogeneous, then the transition matrix **P** is the same after each step, so the *k*-step transition probability can be computed as the *k*-th power of the transition matrix, **P***k*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is irreducible and aperiodic, then there is a unique stationary distribution π.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] where **1** is the column vector with all entries equal to 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This is stated by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If, by whatever means, ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }\mathbf {P} ^{k}}$ is found, then the stationary distribution of the Markov chain in question can be easily determined for any starting distribution, as will be explained below.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Because there are a number of different special cases to consider, the process of finding this limit if it exists can be a lengthy task.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] However, there are many techniques that can assist in finding this limit.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size *n*, and **0***n*,*n* is the zero matrix of size *n*×*n*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Multiplying together stochastic matrices always yields another stochastic matrix, so **Q** must be a stochastic matrix (see the definition above).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] It is sometimes sufficient to use the matrix equation above and the fact that **Q** is a stochastic matrix to solve for **Q**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Here is one method for doing so: first, define the function *f*(**A**) to return the matrix **A** with its right-most column replaced with all 1's.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] One thing to notice is that if **P** has an element **P***i*,*i* on its main diagonal that is equal to 1 and the *i*th row or column is otherwise filled with 0's, then that row or column will remain unchanged in all of the subsequent powers **P***k*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Hence, the *i*th row or column of **Q** will have the 1 and the 0's in the same positions as in **P**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] As stated earlier, from the equation ${\boldsymbol {\pi }}={\boldsymbol {\pi }}\mathbf {P} ,$ (if exists) the stationary (or steady state) distribution **π** is a left eigenvector of row stochastic matrix **P**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Then assuming that **P** is diagonalizable or equivalently that **P** has *n* linearly independent eigenvectors, speed of convergence is elaborated as follows.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Let **U** be the matrix of eigenvectors (each normalized to having an L2 norm equal to 1) where each column is a left eigenvector of **P** and let **Σ** be the diagonal matrix of left eigenvalues of **P**, that is, **Σ** = diag(*λ*1,*λ*2,*λ*3,...,*λ**n*).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since **P** is a row stochastic matrix, its largest left eigenvalue is 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If there is a unique stationary distribution, then the largest eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector is unique too (because there is no other **π** which solves the stationary distribution equation above).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Let **u***i* be the *i*-th column of **U** matrix, that is, **u***i* is the left eigenvector of **P** corresponding to λ*i*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If we multiply **x** with **P** from right and continue this operation with the results, in the end we get the stationary distribution **π**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since **π** is parallel to **u**1(normalized by L2 norm) and **π**(*k*) is a probability vector, **π**(*k*) approaches to **a**1 **u**1 = **π** as *k* → ∞ with a speed in the order of *λ*2/*λ*1 exponentially.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This follows because $|\lambda _{2}|\geq \cdots \geq |\lambda _{n}|,$ hence *λ*2/*λ*1 is the dominant term.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The smaller the ratio is, the faster the convergence is.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Random noise in the state distribution **π** can also speed up this convergence to the stationary distribution.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov chain $(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is defined by a finite or countable state space *S*, a transition rate matrix *Q* with dimensions equal to that of the state space and initial probability distribution defined on the state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] For *i* ≠ *j*, the elements *q**ij* are non-negative and describe the rate of the process transitions from state *i* to state *j*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The elements *q**ii* are chosen such that each row of the transition rate matrix sums to zero, while the row-sums of a probability transition matrix in a (discrete) Markov chain are all equal to one.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] There are three equivalent definitions of the process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Let $X_{t}$ be the random variable describing the state of the process at time *t*, and assume the process is in a state *i* at time *t*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Then, knowing $X_{t}=i$ , $X_{t+h}=j$ is independent of previous values $\left(X_{s}:s<t\right)$ , and as *h* → 0 for all *j* and for all *t*, $\Pr(X(t+h)=j\mid X(t)=i)=\delta _{ij}+q_{ij}h+o(h),$ where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, using the little-o notation.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The $q_{ij}$ can be seen as measuring how quickly the transition from *i* to *j* happens.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Define a discrete-time Markov chain *Y**n* to describe the *n*th jump of the process and variables *S*1, *S*2, *S*3, ... to describe holding times in each of the states where *S**i* follows the exponential distribution with rate parameter −*q**Y**i**Y**i*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] with initial condition P(0) is the identity matrix.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] "Locally interacting Markov chains" are Markov chains with an evolution that takes into account the state of other Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This corresponds to the situation when the state space has a (Cartesian-) product form.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] See interacting particle system and stochastic cellular automata (probabilistic cellular automata).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] See for instance *Interaction of Markov Processes* or.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Many results for discrete-time Markov chains with finite state space can be generalized to chains with uncountable state space through Harris chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The use of Markov chains in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods covers cases where the process follows a continuous state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The definition of Markov processes in continuous time with general state space is more technical than the above.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov process $X=(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a stochastic process adapted to a filtration $\mathbb {F} =({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ with values in a locally compact Polish space $(S,{\mathcal {B}}(S))$ (e.g., $(\mathbb {R} ,{\mathcal {B}}(\mathbb {R} ))$ ).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The latter essentially ensures that the conditional expectations of $X_{t}$ are regular, which, in simple terms, means that they behave "nicely".
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The function $(t,x,A)\mapsto P_{t}(x,A)$ is the so-called *transition function* of X and $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ the *transition semigroup* of the process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Transition functions are generalizations of the transition matrices used in the setting with finite state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] where $\delta _{x}$ is the Dirac-measure in x , and $X:\Omega \times [0,\infty )\to S$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Or, if no probability measure P has been specified, the above equation defines a measure $P^{x}:=P(\cdot \mid X_{0}=x)$ on $\sigma (X_{s}:s\geq 0)$ under which the process X started in x is a Markov process by construction.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, Markov processes can be defined either as stochastic processes X on a filtered probability space, or indirectly in terms of a transition semigroup (i.e., the transition probabilities of the process), which induces a probability space under which X has the Markov property.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Two states are said to *communicate* with each other if both are reachable from one another by a sequence of transitions that have positive probability.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This is an equivalence relation which yields a set of communicating classes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A class is *closed* if the probability of leaving the class is zero.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is *irreducible* if there is one communicating class, the state space.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* has period *k* if *k* is the greatest common divisor of the number of transitions by which *i* can be reached, starting from *i*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The state is *periodic* if $k>1$ ; otherwise $k=1$ and the state is *aperiodic*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *transient* if, starting from *i*, there is a non-zero probability that the chain will never return to *i*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] It is called *recurrent* (or *persistent*) otherwise.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] State *i* is *positive recurrent* if $M_{i}$ is finite and *null recurrent* otherwise.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Periodicity, transience, recurrence and positive and null recurrence are class properties — that is, if one state has the property then all states in its communicating class have the property.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is called *absorbing* if there are no outgoing transitions from the state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since periodicity is a class property, if a Markov chain is irreducible, then all its states have the same period.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In particular, if one state is aperiodic, then the whole Markov chain is aperiodic.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If a finite Markov chain is irreducible, then all states are positive recurrent, and it has a unique stationary distribution given by $\pi _{i}=1/E[T_{i}]$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *ergodic* if it is aperiodic and positive recurrent.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, a state *i* is ergodic if it is recurrent, has a period of 1, and has finite mean recurrence time.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If all states in an irreducible Markov chain are ergodic, then the chain is said to be ergodic.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Equivalently, there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] It can be shown that a finite state irreducible Markov chain is ergodic if it has an aperiodic state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain with more than one state and just one out-going transition per state is either not irreducible or not aperiodic, hence cannot be ergodic.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call any irreducible, positive recurrent Markov chains ergodic, even periodic ones.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In fact, merely irreducible Markov chains correspond to ergodic processes, defined according to ergodic theory.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call a matrix *primitive* if there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The *index of primitivity*, or *exponent*, of a regular matrix, is the smallest k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The exponent is purely a graph-theoretic property, since it depends only on whether each entry of M is zero or positive, and therefore can be found on a directed graph with $\mathrm {sign} (M)$ as its adjacency matrix.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] There are several combinatorial results about the exponent when there are finitely many states.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If a Markov chain has a stationary distribution, then it can be converted to a measure-preserving dynamical system: Let the probability space be $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ , where $\Sigma$ is the set of all states for the Markov chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Let the sigma-algebra on the probability space be generated by the cylinder sets.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Let the probability measure be generated by the stationary distribution, and the Markov chain transition.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Similarly we can construct such a dynamical system with $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ instead.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Since *irreducible* Markov chains with finite state spaces have a unique stationary distribution, the above construction is unambiguous for irreducible Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In ergodic theory, a measure-preserving dynamical system is called *ergodic* if any measurable subset S such that $T^{-1}(S)=S$ implies $S=\emptyset$ or $\Omega$ (up to a null set).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Given a Markov chain with a stationary distribution that is strictly positive on all states, the Markov chain is *irreducible* if its corresponding measure-preserving dynamical system is *ergodic*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] In some cases, apparently non-Markovian processes may still have Markovian representations, constructed by expanding the concept of the "current" and "future" states.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] For example, let *X* be a non-Markovian process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Then define a process *Y*, such that each state of *Y* represents a time-interval of states of *X*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If *Y* has the Markov property, then it is a Markovian representation of *X*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] An example of a non-Markovian process with a Markovian representation is an autoregressive time series of order greater than one.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The *hitting time* is the time, starting in a given set of states, until the chain arrives in a given state or set of states.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The distribution of such a time period has a phase type distribution.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The simplest such distribution is that of a single exponentially distributed transition.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] For a general Markov process X in continuous time (a CTMC or a process with general state space), the reverse process ${\overleftarrow {X}}=(X_{T-t})_{t\in [0,T]}$ from a fixed time $T>0$ is again a Markov process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] This follows directly from the Markov property: Informally speaking, the future and the past are independent given the present.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Under time-reversal, their roles are just interchanged.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] However, the reverse process is not time-homogeneous in general.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] If X is a CTMC, then by Kelly's lemma ${\overleftarrow {X}}$ has the same stationary distribution as the forward process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A chain is said to be *reversible* if the reversed process is the same as the forward process (in distribution).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov's criterion states that the necessary and sufficient condition for a Markov chain to be reversible is that the product of transition rates around a closed loop must be the same in both directions.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] One method of finding the stationary probability distribution, π, of an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain, *Q*, is by first finding its **embedded Markov chain (EMC)**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Strictly speaking, the EMC is a regular discrete-time Markov chain, sometimes referred to as a **jump process**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Each element of the one-step transition probability matrix of the EMC, *S*, is denoted by *s**ij*, and represents the conditional probability of transitioning from state *i* into state *j*.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] where *I* is the identity matrix and diag(*Q*) is the diagonal matrix formed by selecting the main diagonal from the matrix *Q* and setting all other elements to zero.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] with $\varphi$ being a row vector, such that all elements in $\varphi$ are greater than 0 and $\|\varphi \|_{1}$ = 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] (*S* may be periodic, even if *Q* is not.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Another discrete-time process that may be derived from a continuous-time Markov chain is a δ-skeleton—the (discrete-time) Markov chain formed by observing *X*(*t*) at intervals of δ units of time.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The random variables *X*(0), *X*(δ), *X*(2δ), ... give the sequence of states visited by the δ-skeleton.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov models are used to model changing systems.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme is a special case of a Markov chain where the transition probability matrix has identical rows, which means that the next state is independent of even the current state (in addition to being independent of the past states).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme with only two possible states is known as a Bernoulli process.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Note, however, by the Ornstein isomorphism theorem, that every aperiodic and irreducible Markov chain is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; thus, one might equally claim that Markov chains are a "special case" of Bernoulli schemes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism generally requires a complicated recoding.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism theorem is even a bit stronger: it states that *any* stationary stochastic process is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; the Markov chain is just one such example.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] When the Markov matrix is replaced by the adjacency matrix of a finite graph, the resulting shift is termed a **topological Markov chain** or a **subshift of finite type**.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov matrix that is compatible with the adjacency matrix can then provide a measure on the subshift.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p01] Many chaotic dynamical systems are isomorphic to topological Markov chains; examples include diffeomorphisms of closed manifolds, the Prouhet–Thue–Morse system, the Chacon system, sofic systems, context-free systems and block-coding systems.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains have been employed in a wide range of topics across the natural and social sciences, and in technological applications.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] For example, a thermodynamic state operates under a probability distribution that is difficult or expensive to acquire.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Therefore, Markov Chain Monte Carlo method can be used to draw samples randomly from a black-box to approximate the probability distribution of attributes over a range of objects.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in lattice QCD simulations.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The enzyme (E) binds a substrate (S) and produces a product (P).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Each reaction is a state transition in a Markov chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] A reaction network is a chemical system involving multiple reactions and chemical species.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The simplest stochastic models of such networks treat the system as a continuous time Markov chain with the state being the number of molecules of each species and with reactions modeled as possible transitions of the chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains and continuous-time Markov processes are useful in chemistry when physical systems closely approximate the Markov property.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] For example, imagine a large number *n* of molecules in solution in state A, each of which can undergo a chemical reaction to state B with a certain average rate.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Perhaps the molecule is an enzyme, and the states refer to how it is folded.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The state of any single enzyme follows a Markov chain, and since the molecules are essentially independent of each other, the number of molecules in state A or B at a time is *n* times the probability a given molecule is in that state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The classical model of enzyme activity, Michaelis–Menten kinetics, can be viewed as a Markov chain, where at each time step the reaction proceeds in some direction.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] While Michaelis-Menten is fairly straightforward, far more complicated reaction networks can also be modeled with Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm based on a Markov chain was also used to focus the fragment-based growth of chemicals in silico towards a desired class of compounds such as drugs or natural products.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] As a molecule is grown, a fragment is selected from the nascent molecule as the "current" state.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] It is not aware of its past (that is, it is not aware of what is already bonded to it).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] It then transitions to the next state when a fragment is attached to it.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The transition probabilities are trained on databases of authentic classes of compounds.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Also, the growth (and composition) of copolymers may be modeled using Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Based on the reactivity ratios of the monomers that make up the growing polymer chain, the chain's composition may be calculated (for example, whether monomers tend to add in alternating fashion or in long runs of the same monomer).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Due to steric effects, second-order Markov effects may also play a role in the growth of some polymer chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Similarly, it has been suggested that the crystallization and growth of some epitaxial superlattice oxide materials can be accurately described by Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in various areas of biology.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used throughout information processing.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Such idealized models can capture many of the statistical regularities of systems.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Even without describing the full structure of the system perfectly, such signal models can make possible very effective data compression through entropy encoding techniques such as arithmetic coding.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] They also allow effective state estimation and pattern recognition.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains also play an important role in reinforcement learning.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also the basis for hidden Markov models, which are an important tool in such diverse fields as telephone networks (which use the Viterbi algorithm for error correction), speech recognition and bioinformatics (such as in rearrangements detection).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The LZMA lossless data compression algorithm combines Markov chains with Lempel-Ziv compression to achieve very high compression ratios.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are the basis for the analytical treatment of queues (queueing theory).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Agner Krarup Erlang initiated the subject in 1917.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] This makes them critical for optimizing the performance of telecommunications networks, where messages must often compete for limited resources (such as bandwidth).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Numerous queueing models use continuous-time Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The PageRank of a webpage as used by Google is defined by a Markov chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] It is the probability to be at page i in the stationary distribution on the following Markov chain on all (known) webpages.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] If N is the number of known webpages, and a page i has $k_{i}$ outgoing links from it then it has transition probability ${\frac {\alpha }{k_{i}}}+{\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are linked to and ${\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are not linked to.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The parameter $\alpha$ is taken to be about 0.85.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov models have also been used to analyze web navigation behavior of users.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] A user's web link transition on a particular website can be modeled using first- or second-order Markov models and can be used to make predictions regarding future navigation and to personalize the web page for an individual user.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain methods have also become very important for generating sequences of random numbers to accurately reflect very complicated desired probability distributions, via a process called Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] In recent years this has revolutionized the practicability of Bayesian inference methods, allowing a wide range of posterior distributions to be simulated and their parameters found numerically.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in finance and economics to model a variety of different phenomena, including the distribution of income, the size distribution of firms, asset prices and market crashes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Champernowne built a Markov chain model of the distribution of income in 1953.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Simon and co-author Charles Bonini used a Markov chain model to derive a stationary Yule distribution of firm sizes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Louis Bachelier was the first to observe that stock prices followed a random walk.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The random walk was later seen as evidence in favor of the efficient-market hypothesis and random walk models were popular in the literature of the 1960s.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Regime-switching models of business cycles were popularized by James D.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Hamilton (1989), who used a Markov chain to model switches between periods of high and low GDP growth (or, alternatively, economic expansions and recessions).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] A more recent example is the Markov switching multifractal model of Laurent E.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Fisher, which builds upon the convenience of earlier regime-switching models.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] It uses an arbitrarily large Markov chain to drive the level of volatility of asset returns.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Dynamic macroeconomics makes heavy use of Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] An example is using Markov chains to exogenously model prices of equity (stock) in a general equilibrium setting.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Credit rating agencies produce annual tables of the transition probabilities for bonds of different credit ratings.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are generally used in describing path-dependent arguments, where current structural configurations condition future outcomes.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] An example is the reformulation of the idea, originally due to Karl Marx's *Das Kapital*, tying economic development to the rise of capitalism.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are employed in algorithmic music composition, particularly in software such as Csound, Max, and SuperCollider.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] In a first-order chain, the states of the system become note or pitch values, and a probability vector for each note is constructed, completing a transition probability matrix (see below).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm is constructed to produce output note values based on the transition matrix weightings, which could be MIDI note values, frequency (Hz), or any other desirable metric.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] A second-order Markov chain can be introduced by considering the current state *and* also the previous state, as indicated in the second table.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Higher, *n*th-order chains tend to "group" particular notes together, while 'breaking off' into other patterns and sequences occasionally.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] These higher-order chains tend to generate results with a sense of phrasal structure, rather than the 'aimless wandering' produced by a first-order system.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used structurally, as in Xenakis's Analogique A and B.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also used in systems which use a Markov model to react interactively to music input.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Usually musical systems need to enforce specific control constraints on the finite-length sequences they generate, but control constraints are not compatible with Markov models, since they induce long-range dependencies that violate the Markov hypothesis of limited memory.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] In order to overcome this limitation, a new approach has been proposed.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used to model many games of chance.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] The children's games Snakes and Ladders and "Hi Ho!
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Cherry-O", for example, are represented exactly by Markov chains.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] At each turn, the player starts in a given state (on a given square) and from there has fixed odds of moving to certain other states (squares).
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain models have been used in advanced baseball analysis since 1960, although their use is still rare.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Each half-inning of a baseball game fits the Markov chain state when the number of runners and outs are considered.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] During any at-bat, there are 24 possible combinations of number of outs and position of the runners.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Mark Pankin shows that Markov chain models can be used to evaluate runs created for both individual players as well as a team.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] He also discusses various kinds of strategies and play conditions: how Markov chain models have been used to analyze statistics for game situations such as bunting and base stealing and differences when playing on grass vs.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes can also be used to generate superficially real-looking text given a sample document.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes are used in a variety of recreational "parody generator" software (see dissociated press, Jeff Harrison, Mark V.
[src:autoregressive-models/markov-chain-p02] Several open-source text generation libraries using Markov chains exist.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In artificial neural networks, **recurrent neural networks** (**RNNs**) are designed for processing sequential data, such as text, speech, and time series, where the order of elements is important.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Unlike feedforward neural networks, which process inputs independently, RNNs utilize recurrent connections, where the output of a neuron at one time step is fed back as input to the network at the next time step.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This enables RNNs to capture temporal dependencies and patterns within sequences.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The fundamental building block of RNN is the *recurrent unit*, which maintains a *hidden state*—a form of memory that is updated at each time step based on the current input and the previous hidden state.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This feedback mechanism allows the network to learn from past inputs and incorporate that knowledge into its current processing.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] RNNs have been successfully applied to tasks such as unsegmented, connected handwriting recognition, speech recognition, natural language processing, and neural machine translation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] However, traditional RNNs suffer from the vanishing gradient problem, which limits their ability to learn long-range dependencies.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This issue was addressed by the development of the long short-term memory (LSTM) architecture in 1997, making it the standard RNN variant for handling long-term dependencies.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Later, gated recurrent units (GRUs) were introduced as a more computationally efficient alternative.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Nevertheless, RNNs remain relevant for applications where computational efficiency, real-time processing, or the inherent sequential nature of data is crucial.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex formed by parallel fiber, Purkinje cells, and granule cells.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In 1933, Lorente de Nó discovered "recurrent, reciprocal connections" by Golgi's method, and proposed that excitatory loops explain certain aspects of the vestibulo-ocular reflex.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] During 1940s, multiple people proposed the existence of feedback in the brain, which was a contrast to the previous understanding of the neural system as a purely feedforward structure.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943), which proposed the McCulloch-Pitts neuron model, considered networks that contains cycles.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They were both interested in closed loops as possible explanations for e.g. epilepsy and causalgia.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Recurrent inhibition was proposed in 1946 as a negative feedback mechanism in motor control.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Neural feedback loops were a common topic of discussion at the Macy conferences.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] See for an extensive review of recurrent neural network models in neuroscience.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Frank Rosenblatt in 1960 published "close-loop cross-coupled perceptrons", which are 3-layered perceptron networks whose middle layer contains recurrent connections that change by a Hebbian learning rule.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Similar networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971, Shun'ichi Amari in 1972, and William A.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Little in 1974, who was acknowledged by Hopfield in his 1982 paper.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Another origin of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The Ising model was developed by Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising in the 1920s as a simple statistical mechanical model of magnets at equilibrium.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Glauber in 1963 studied the Ising model evolving in time, as a process towards equilibrium (Glauber dynamics), adding in the component of time.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The Sherrington–Kirkpatrick model of spin glass, published in 1975, is the Hopfield network with random initialization.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Sherrington and Kirkpatrick found that it is highly likely for the energy function of the SK model to have many local minima.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In the 1982 paper, Hopfield applied this recently developed theory to study the Hopfield network with binary activation functions.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In a 1984 paper he extended this to continuous activation functions.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It became a standard model for the study of neural networks through statistical mechanics.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Modern RNN networks are mainly based on two architectures: LSTM and BRNN.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] At the resurgence of neural networks in the 1980s, recurrent networks were studied again.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They were sometimes called "iterated nets".
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Long short-term memory (LSTM) networks were invented by Hochreiter and Schmidhuber in 1995 and set accuracy records in multiple applications domains.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Bidirectional recurrent neural networks (BRNN) use two RNNs that process the same input in opposite directions.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] These two are often combined, giving the bidirectional LSTM architecture.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Around 2006, bidirectional LSTM started to revolutionize speech recognition, outperforming traditional models in certain speech applications.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They also improved large-vocabulary speech recognition and text-to-speech synthesis and was used in Google voice search, and dictation on Android devices.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They broke records for improved machine translation, language modeling and Multilingual Language Processing.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Also, LSTM combined with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) improved automatic image captioning.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The idea of encoder-decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The papers most commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two papers from 2014.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A seq2seq architecture employs two RNN, typically LSTM, an "encoder" and a "decoder", for sequence transduction, such as machine translation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They became state of the art in machine translation, and were instrumental in the development of attention mechanisms and transformers.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN-based model can be factored into two parts: configuration and architecture.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Multiple RNNs can be combined in a data flow, and the data flow itself is the configuration.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each RNN itself may have any architecture, including LSTM, GRU, etc.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In words, it is a neural network that maps an input $x_{t}$ into an output $y_{t}$ , with the hidden vector $h_{t}$ playing the role of "memory", a partial record of all previous input-output pairs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] At each step, it transforms input to an output, and modifies its "memory" to help it to better perform future processing.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The illustration to the right may be misleading to many because practical neural network topologies are frequently organized in "layers" and the drawing gives that appearance.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] However, what appears to be layers are, in fact, different steps in time, "unfolded" to produce the appearance of layers.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A **stacked RNN**, or **deep RNN**, is composed of multiple RNNs stacked one above the other.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each layer operates as a stand-alone RNN, and each layer's output sequence is used as the input sequence to the layer above.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] There is no conceptual limit to the depth of stacked RNN.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A **bidirectional RNN** (biRNN) is composed of two RNNs, one processing the input sequence in one direction, and another in the opposite direction.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Bidirectional RNN allows the model to process a token both in the context of what came before it and what came after it.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] By stacking multiple bidirectional RNNs together, the model can process a token increasingly contextually.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The ELMo model (2018) is a stacked bidirectional LSTM which takes character-level as inputs and produces word-level embeddings.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Two RNNs can be run front-to-back in an **encoder-decoder** configuration.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The encoder RNN processes an input sequence into a sequence of hidden vectors, and the decoder RNN processes the sequence of hidden vectors to an output sequence, with an optional attention mechanism.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This was used to construct state of the art neural machine translators during the 2014–2017 period.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This was an instrumental step towards the development of transformers.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN may process data with more than one dimension.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] PixelRNN processes two-dimensional data, with many possible directions.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] For example, the row-by-row direction processes an $n\times n$ grid of vectors $x_{i,j}$ in the following order: $x_{1,1},x_{1,2},\dots ,x_{1,n},x_{2,1},x_{2,2},\dots ,x_{2,n},\dots ,x_{n,n}$ The **diagonal BiLSTM** uses two LSTMs to process the same grid.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] One processes it from the top-left corner to the bottom-right, such that it processes $x_{i,j}$ depending on its hidden state and cell state on the top and the left side: $h_{i-1,j},c_{i-1,j}$ and $h_{i,j-1},c_{i,j-1}$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The other processes it from the top-right corner to the bottom-left.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The **Hopfield network** is an RNN in which all connections across layers are equally sized.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It requires stationary inputs and is thus not a general RNN, as it does not process sequences of patterns.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] However, it guarantees that it will converge.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] If the connections are trained using Hebbian learning, then the Hopfield network can perform as robust content-addressable memory, resistant to connection alteration.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] An **Elman network** is a three-layer network (arranged horizontally as *x*, *y*, and *z* in the illustration) with the addition of a set of context units (*u* in the illustration).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The middle (hidden) layer is connected to these context units fixed with a weight of one.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] At each time step, the input is fed forward and a learning rule is applied.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The fixed back-connections save a copy of the previous values of the hidden units in the context units (since they propagate over the connections before the learning rule is applied).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Thus the network can maintain a sort of state, allowing it to perform tasks such as sequence-prediction that are beyond the power of a standard multilayer perceptron.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Elman and Jordan networks are also known as "Simple recurrent networks" (SRN).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Many applications use stacks of LSTMs, for which it is called "deep LSTM".
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] LSTM can learn to recognize context-sensitive languages unlike previous models based on hidden Markov models (HMM) and similar concepts.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Their performance on polyphonic music modeling and speech signal modeling was found to be similar to that of long short-term memory.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] There does not appear to be particular performance difference between LSTM and GRU.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Introduced by Bart Kosko, a bidirectional associative memory (BAM) network is a variant of a Hopfield network that stores associative data as a vector.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The bidirectionality comes from passing information through a matrix and its transpose.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Typically, bipolar encoding is preferred to binary encoding of the associative pairs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Recently, stochastic BAM models using Markov stepping are optimized for increased network stability and relevance to real-world applications.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A BAM network has two layers, either of which can be driven as an input to recall an association and produce an output on the other layer.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A **recursive neural network** is created by applying the same set of weights recursively over a differentiable graph-like structure by traversing the structure in topological order.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Such networks are typically also trained by the reverse mode of automatic differentiation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They can process distributed representations of structure, such as logical terms.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A special case of recursive neural networks is the RNN whose structure corresponds to a linear chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Recursive neural networks have been applied to natural language processing.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The *recursive neural tensor network* uses a tensor-based composition function for all nodes in the tree.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Recurrent neural networks are Turing complete and can run arbitrary programs to process arbitrary sequences of inputs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN can be trained into a conditionally generative model of sequences, aka **autoregression**.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Concretely, let us consider the problem of machine translation, that is, given a sequence $(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n})$ of English words, the model is to produce a sequence $(y_{1},\dots ,y_{m})$ of French words.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Now, during training, the encoder half of the model would first ingest $(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n})$ , then the decoder half would start generating a sequence $({\hat {y}}_{1},{\hat {y}}_{2},\dots ,{\hat {y}}_{l})$ .
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The problem is that if the model makes a mistake early on, say at ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ , then subsequent tokens are likely to also be mistakes.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This makes it inefficient for the model to obtain a learning signal, since the model would mostly learn to shift ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ towards $y_{2}$ , but not the others.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Gradient descent is a first-order iterative optimization algorithm for finding the minimum of a function.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In neural networks, it can be used to minimize the error term by changing each weight in proportion to the derivative of the error with respect to that weight, provided the non-linear activation functions are differentiable.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The standard method for training RNN by gradient descent is the "backpropagation through time" (BPTT) algorithm, which is a special case of the general algorithm of backpropagation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A more computationally expensive online variant is called "Real-Time Recurrent Learning" or RTRL, which is an instance of automatic differentiation in the forward accumulation mode with stacked tangent vectors.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Unlike BPTT, this algorithm is local in time but not local in space.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In this context, local in space means that a unit's weight vector can be updated using only information stored in the connected units and the unit itself such that update complexity of a single unit is linear in the dimensionality of the weight vector.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Local in time means that the updates take place continually (on-line) and depend only on the most recent time step rather than on multiple time steps within a given time horizon as in BPTT.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Biological neural networks appear to be local with respect to both time and space.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] An online hybrid between BPTT and RTRL with intermediate complexity exists, along with variants for continuous time.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A major problem with gradient descent for standard RNN architectures is that error gradients vanish exponentially quickly with the size of the time lag between important events.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] LSTM combined with a BPTT/RTRL hybrid learning method attempts to overcome these problems.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This problem is also solved in the independently recurrent neural network (IndRNN) by reducing the context of a neuron to its own past state and the cross-neuron information can then be explored in the following layers.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Memories of different ranges including long-term memory can be learned without the gradient vanishing and exploding problems.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The online algorithm called **causal recursive backpropagation** (CRBP), implements and combines BPTT and RTRL paradigms for locally recurrent networks.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It works with the most general locally recurrent networks.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The CRBP algorithm can minimize the global error term.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This fact improves the stability of the algorithm, providing a unifying view of gradient calculation techniques for recurrent networks with local feedback.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] One approach to gradient information computation in RNNs with arbitrary architectures is based on signal-flow graphs diagrammatic derivation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It uses the BPTT batch algorithm, based on Lee's theorem for network sensitivity calculations.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It was proposed by Wan and Beaufays, while its fast online version was proposed by Campolucci, Uncini and Piazza.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The connectionist temporal classification (CTC) is a specialized loss function for training RNNs for sequence modeling problems where the timing is variable.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Training the weights in a neural network can be modeled as a non-linear global optimization problem.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A target function can be formed to evaluate the fitness or error of a particular weight vector as follows: First, the weights in the network are set according to the weight vector.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Next, the network is evaluated against the training sequence.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Typically, the sum-squared difference between the predictions and the target values specified in the training sequence is used to represent the error of the current weight vector.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Arbitrary global optimization techniques may then be used to minimize this target function.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The most common global optimization method for training RNNs is genetic algorithms, especially in unstructured networks.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Initially, the genetic algorithm is encoded with the neural network weights in a predefined manner where one gene in the chromosome represents one weight link.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The whole network is represented as a single chromosome.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Many chromosomes make up the population; therefore, many different neural networks are evolved until a stopping criterion is satisfied.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The fitness function evaluates the stopping criterion as it receives the mean-squared error reciprocal from each network during training.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Therefore, the goal of the genetic algorithm is to maximize the fitness function, reducing the mean-squared error.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Other global (and/or evolutionary) optimization techniques may be used to seek a good set of weights, such as simulated annealing or particle swarm optimization.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The independently recurrent neural network (IndRNN) addresses the gradient vanishing and exploding problems in the traditional fully connected RNN.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each neuron in one layer only receives its own past state as context information (instead of full connectivity to all other neurons in this layer) and thus neurons are independent of each other's history.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The gradient backpropagation can be regulated to avoid gradient vanishing and exploding in order to keep long or short-term memory.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The cross-neuron information is explored in the next layers.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] IndRNN can be robustly trained with non-saturated nonlinear functions such as ReLU.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Deep networks can be trained using skip connections.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The *neural history compressor* is an unsupervised stack of RNNs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] At the input level, it learns to predict its next input from the previous inputs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Only unpredictable inputs of some RNN in the hierarchy become inputs to the next higher level RNN, which therefore recomputes its internal state only rarely.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each higher level RNN thus studies a compressed representation of the information in the RNN below.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This is done such that the input sequence can be precisely reconstructed from the representation at the highest level.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The system effectively minimizes the description length or the negative logarithm of the probability of the data.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Given a lot of learnable predictability in the incoming data sequence, the highest level RNN can use supervised learning to easily classify even deep sequences with long intervals between important events.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] It is possible to distill the RNN hierarchy into two RNNs: the "conscious" chunker (higher level) and the "subconscious" automatizer (lower level).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Once the chunker has learned to predict and compress inputs that are unpredictable by the automatizer, then the automatizer can be forced in the next learning phase to predict or imitate through additional units the hidden units of the more slowly changing chunker.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This makes it easy for the automatizer to learn appropriate, rarely changing memories across long intervals.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In turn, this helps the automatizer to make many of its once unpredictable inputs predictable, such that the chunker can focus on the remaining unpredictable events.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A generative model partially overcame the vanishing gradient problem of automatic differentiation or backpropagation in neural networks in 1992.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In 1993, such a system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Second-order RNNs use higher order weights $w{}_{ijk}$ instead of the standard $w{}_{ij}$ weights, and states can be a product.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This allows a direct mapping to a finite-state machine both in training, and representation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Long short-term memory is an example of this but has no such formal mappings or proof of stability.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Hierarchical recurrent neural networks (HRNN) connect their neurons in various ways to decompose hierarchical behavior into useful subprograms.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Such hierarchical structures of cognition are present in theories of memory presented by philosopher Henri Bergson, whose philosophical views have inspired hierarchical models.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Hierarchical recurrent neural networks are useful in forecasting, helping to predict disaggregated inflation components of the consumer price index (CPI).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The HRNN model leverages information from higher levels in the CPI hierarchy to enhance lower-level predictions.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Evaluation of a substantial dataset from the US CPI-U index demonstrates the superior performance of the HRNN model compared to various established inflation prediction methods.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Generally, a recurrent multilayer perceptron network (RMLPN) consists of cascaded subnetworks, each containing multiple layers of nodes.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each subnetwork is feed-forward except for the last layer, which can have feedback connections.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Each of these subnets is connected only by feed-forward connections.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] With such varied neuronal activities, continuous sequences of any set of behaviors are segmented into reusable primitives, which in turn are flexibly integrated into diverse sequential behaviors.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The biological approval of such a type of hierarchy was discussed in the memory-prediction theory of brain function by Hawkins in his book *On Intelligence*.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Such a hierarchy also agrees with theories of memory posited by philosopher Henri Bergson, which have been incorporated into an MTRNN model.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Greg Snider of HP Labs describes a system of cortical computing with memristive nanodevices.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The memristors (memory resistors) are implemented by thin film materials in which the resistance is electrically tuned via the transport of ions or oxygen vacancies within the film.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] DARPA's SyNAPSE project has funded IBM Research and HP Labs, in collaboration with the Boston University Department of Cognitive and Neural Systems (CNS), to develop neuromorphic architectures that may be based on memristive systems.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Memristive networks are a particular type of physical neural network that have very similar properties to (Little-)Hopfield networks, as they have continuous dynamics, a limited memory capacity and natural relaxation via the minimization of a function which is asymptotic to the Ising model.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] In this sense, the dynamics of a memristive circuit have the advantage compared to a Resistor-Capacitor network to have a more interesting non-linear behavior.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] From this point of view, engineering analog memristive networks account for a peculiar type of neuromorphic engineering in which the device behavior depends on the circuit wiring or topology.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The evolution of these networks can be studied analytically using variations of the Caravelli-Traversa-Di Ventra equation.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A continuous-time recurrent neural network (CTRNN) uses a system of ordinary differential equations to model the effects on a neuron of the incoming inputs.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They are typically analyzed by dynamical systems theory.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Many RNN models in neuroscience are continuous-time.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] CTRNNs have been applied to evolutionary robotics where they have been used to address vision, co-operation, and minimal cognitive behaviour.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Note that, by the Shannon sampling theorem, discrete-time recurrent neural networks can be viewed as continuous-time recurrent neural networks where the differential equations have transformed into equivalent difference equations.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This transformation can be thought of as occurring after the post-synaptic node activation functions $y_{i}(t)$ have been low-pass filtered but prior to sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] They are in fact recursive neural networks with a particular structure: that of a linear chain.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] From a time-series perspective, RNNs can appear as nonlinear versions of finite impulse response and infinite impulse response filters and also as a nonlinear autoregressive exogenous model (NARX).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] RNN has infinite impulse response whereas convolutional neural network has finite impulse response.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Both classes of networks exhibit temporal dynamic behavior.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] A finite impulse recurrent network is a directed acyclic graph that can be unrolled and replaced with a strictly feedforward neural network, while an infinite impulse recurrent network is a directed cyclic graph that cannot be unrolled.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] The effect of memory-based learning for the recognition of sequences can also be implemented by a more biological-based model which uses the silencing mechanism exhibited in neurons with a relatively high frequency spiking activity.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Additional stored states and the storage under direct control by the network can be added to both infinite-impulse and finite-impulse networks.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Another network or graph can also replace the storage if that incorporates time delays or has feedback loops.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Such controlled states are referred to as gated states or gated memory and are part of long short-term memory networks (LSTMs) and gated recurrent units.
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] This is also called Feedback Neural Network (FNN).
[src:autoregressive-models/recurrent-neural-network] Modern libraries provide runtime-optimized implementations of the above functionality or allow to speed up the slow loop by just-in-time compilation.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In statistics, quality assurance, and survey methodology, **sampling** is the selection of a subset of individuals from within a statistical population to estimate characteristics of the whole population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The subset, called a **statistical sample** (or **sample**, for short), is meant to reflect the whole population, and statisticians attempt to collect samples that are representative of the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sampling has lower costs and faster data collection compared to a census recording data from the entire population (in many cases, collecting the whole population is impossible, like getting sizes of all stars in the universe).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Thus, it can provide insights in cases where it is infeasible to measure an entire population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Each observation measures one or more properties (such as weight, location, colour or mass) of independent objects or individuals.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, weights can be applied to the data to adjust for the sample design, particularly in stratified sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Results from probability theory and statistical theory are employed to guide the practice.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In business and medical research, sampling is widely used for gathering information about a population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Acceptance sampling is used to determine if a production lot of material meets the governing specifications.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Random sampling by using lots is an old idea, mentioned several times in the Bible.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In 1786, Pierre Simon Laplace estimated the population of France by using a sample, along with ratio estimator.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] He also computed probabilistic estimates of the error.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] These were not expressed as modern confidence intervals but as the sample size that would be needed to achieve a particular upper bound on the sampling error with probability 1000/1001.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] His estimates used Bayes' theorem with a uniform prior probability and assumed that his sample was random.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Alexander Ivanovich Chuprov introduced sample surveys to Imperial Russia in the 1870s.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the US, the 1936 *Literary Digest* prediction of a Republican win in the presidential election went badly awry, due to severe bias [1].
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] More than two million people responded to the study with their names obtained through magazine subscription lists and telephone directories.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It was not appreciated that these lists were heavily biased towards Republicans and the resulting sample, though very large, was deeply flawed.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Successful statistical practice is based on focused problem definition.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In sampling, this includes defining the "population" from which our sample is drawn.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A population can be defined as including all people or items with the characteristics one wishes to understand.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Because there is very rarely enough time or money to gather information from everyone or everything in a population, the goal becomes finding a representative sample (or subset) of that population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sometimes what defines a population is obvious.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, a manufacturer needs to decide whether a batch of material from production is of high enough quality to be released to the customer or should be scrapped or reworked due to poor quality.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In this case, the batch is the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Although the population of interest often consists of physical objects, sometimes it is necessary to sample over time, space, or some combination of these dimensions.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For instance, an investigation of supermarket staffing could examine checkout line length at various times, or a study on endangered penguins might aim to understand their usage of various hunting grounds over time.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For the time dimension, the focus may be on periods or discrete occasions.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In other cases, the examined 'population' may be even less tangible.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, Joseph Jagger studied the behaviour of roulette wheels at a casino in Monte Carlo, and used this to identify a biased wheel.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In this case, the 'population' Jagger wanted to investigate was the overall behaviour of the wheel (i.e. the probability distribution of its results over infinitely many trials), while his 'sample' was formed from observed results from that wheel.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Similar considerations arise when taking repeated measurements of properties of materials such as the electrical conductivity of copper.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This situation often arises when seeking knowledge about the cause system of which the *observed* population is an outcome.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In such cases, sampling theory may treat the observed population as a sample from a larger 'superpopulation'.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, a researcher might study the success rate of a new 'quit smoking' program on a test group of 100 patients, in order to predict the effects of the program if it were made available nationwide.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Here the superpopulation is "everybody in the country, given access to this treatment" – a group that does not yet exist since the program is not yet available to all.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The population from which the sample is drawn may not be the same as the population from which information is desired.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Often there is a large but not complete overlap between these two groups due to frame issues etc.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sometimes they may be entirely separate – for instance, one might study rats in order to get a better understanding of human health, or one might study records from people born in 2008 in order to make predictions about people born in 2009.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Time spent in making the sampled population and population of concern precise is often well spent because it raises many issues, ambiguities, and questions that would otherwise have been overlooked at this stage.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the most straightforward case, such as the sampling of a batch of material from production (acceptance sampling by lots), it would be most desirable to identify and measure every single item in the population and to include any one of them in our sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] However, in the more general case this is not usually possible or practical.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] There is no way to identify all rats in the set of all rats.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Where voting is not compulsory, there is no way to identify which people will vote at a forthcoming election (in advance of the election).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] These imprecise populations are not amenable to sampling in any of the ways below and to which we could apply statistical theory.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] As a remedy, we seek a sampling frame which has the property that we can identify every single element and include any in our sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The most straightforward type of frame is a list of elements of the population (preferably the entire population) with appropriate contact information.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, in an opinion poll, possible sampling frames include an electoral register and a telephone directory.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A **probability sample** is a sample in which every unit in the population has a chance (greater than zero) of being selected in the sample, and this probability can be accurately determined.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The combination of these traits makes it possible to produce unbiased estimates of population totals, by weighting sampled units according to their probability of selection.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the above example, not everybody has the same probability of selection; what makes it a probability sample is the fact that each person's probability is known.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] When every element in the population *does* have the same probability of selection, this is known as an 'equal probability of selection' (EPS) design.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Such designs are also referred to as 'self-weighting' because all sampled units are given the same weight.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Probability sampling includes: simple random sampling, systematic sampling, stratified sampling, probability-proportional-to-size sampling, and cluster or multistage sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] 2. involves random selection at some point.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Nonprobability sampling methods include convenience sampling, quota sampling, snowball sampling, and purposive sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In addition, nonresponse effects may turn *any* probability design into a nonprobability design if the characteristics of nonresponse are not well understood, since nonresponse effectively modifies each element's probability of being sampled.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Within any of the types of frames identified above, a variety of sampling methods can be employed individually or in combination.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In a simple random sample (SRS) of a given size, all subsets of a sampling frame have an equal probability of being selected.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Each element of the frame thus has an equal probability of selection: the frame is not subdivided or partitioned.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Furthermore, any given *pair* of elements has the same chance of selection as any other such pair (and similarly for triples, and so on).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This minimizes bias and simplifies analysis of results.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In particular, the variance between individual results within the sample is a good indicator of variance in the overall population, which makes it relatively easy to estimate the accuracy of results.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling can be vulnerable to sampling error because the randomness of the selection may result in a sample that does not reflect the makeup of the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For instance, a simple random sample of ten people from a given country will *on average* produce five men and five women, but any given trial is likely to overrepresent one sex and underrepresent the other.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Systematic and stratified techniques attempt to overcome this problem by "using information about the population" to choose a more "representative" sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Also, simple random sampling can be cumbersome and tedious when sampling from a large target population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In some cases, investigators are interested in research questions specific to subgroups of the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, researchers might be interested in examining whether cognitive ability as a predictor of job performance is equally applicable across racial groups.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling cannot accommodate the needs of researchers in this situation, because it does not provide subsamples of the population, and other sampling strategies, such as stratified sampling, can be used instead.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling (also known as interval sampling) relies on arranging the study population according to some ordering scheme, and then selecting elements at regular intervals through that ordered list.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling involves a random start and then proceeds with the selection of every *k*th element from then onwards.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In this case, *k*=(population size/sample size).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is important that the starting point is not automatically the first in the list, but is instead randomly chosen from within the first to the *k*th element in the list.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A simple example would be to select every 10th name from the telephone directory (an 'every 10th' sample, also referred to as 'sampling with a skip of 10').
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] As long as the starting point is randomized, systematic sampling is a type of probability sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is easy to implement and the stratification induced can make it efficient, *if* the variable by which the list is ordered is correlated with the variable of interest.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] 'Every 10th' sampling is especially useful for efficient sampling from databases.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, suppose we wish to sample people from a long street that starts in a poor area (house No.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] 1) and ends in an expensive district (house No.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A simple random selection of addresses from this street could easily end up with too many from the high end and too few from the low end (or vice versa), leading to an unrepresentative sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Selecting (e.g.) every 10th street number along the street ensures that the sample is spread evenly along the length of the street, representing all of these districts.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] However, systematic sampling is especially vulnerable to periodicities in the list.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] If periodicity is present and the period is a multiple or factor of the interval used, the sample is especially likely to be *un*representative of the overall population, making the scheme less accurate than simple random sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, consider a street where the odd-numbered houses are all on the north (expensive) side of the road, and the even-numbered houses are all on the south (cheap) side.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Another drawback of systematic sampling is that even in scenarios where it is more accurate than SRS, its theoretical properties make it difficult to *quantify* that accuracy.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] As described above, systematic sampling is an EPS method, because all elements have the same probability of selection (in the example given, one in ten).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is *not* 'simple random sampling' because different subsets of the same size have different selection probabilities – e.g., the set {4,14,24,...,994} has a one-in-ten probability of selection, but the set {4,13,24,34,...} has zero probability of selection.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling can also be adapted to a non-EPS approach; for an example, see discussion of PPS samples below.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] When the population embraces a number of distinct categories, the frame can be organized by these categories into separate "strata." Each stratum is then sampled as an independent sub-population, out of which individual elements can be randomly selected.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The ratio of the size of this random selection (or sample) to the size of the population is called a sampling fraction.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] There are several potential benefits to stratified sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] First, dividing the population into distinct, independent strata can enable researchers to draw inferences about specific subgroups that may be lost in a more generalized random sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Second, utilizing a stratified sampling method can lead to more efficient statistical estimates (provided that strata are selected based upon relevance to the criterion in question, instead of availability of the samples).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Even if a stratified sampling approach does not lead to increased statistical efficiency, such a tactic will not result in less efficiency than would simple random sampling, provided that each stratum is proportional to the group's size in the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Finally, since each stratum is treated as an independent population, different sampling approaches can be applied to different strata, potentially enabling researchers to use the approach best suited (or most cost-effective) for each identified subgroup within the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] There are, however, some potential drawbacks to using stratified sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] First, identifying strata and implementing such an approach can increase the cost and complexity of sample selection, as well as leading to increased complexity of population estimates.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Second, when examining multiple criteria, stratifying variables may be related to some, but not to others, further complicating the design, and potentially reducing the utility of the strata.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The variables upon which the population is stratified are strongly correlated with the desired dependent variable.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Allows use of different sampling techniques for different subpopulations.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Improves the accuracy/efficiency of estimation.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Permits greater balancing of statistical power of tests of differences between strata by sampling equal numbers from strata varying widely in size.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Is not useful when there are no homogeneous subgroups.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Stratification is sometimes introduced after the sampling phase in a process called "poststratification".
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This approach is typically implemented due to a lack of prior knowledge of an appropriate stratifying variable or when the experimenter lacks the necessary information to create a stratifying variable during the sampling phase.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Although the method is susceptible to the pitfalls of post hoc approaches, it can provide several benefits in the right situation.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Implementation usually follows a simple random sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In addition to allowing for stratification on an ancillary variable, poststratification can be used to implement weighting, which can improve the precision of a sample's estimates.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Choice-based sampling or oversampling is one of the stratified sampling strategies.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In choice-based sampling, the data are stratified on the target and a sample is taken from each stratum so that rarer target classes will be more represented in the sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The model is then built on this biased sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The effects of the input variables on the target are often estimated with more precision with the choice-based sample even when a smaller overall sample size is taken, compared to a random sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The results usually must be adjusted to correct for the oversampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In some cases the sample designer has access to an "auxiliary variable" or "size measure", believed to be correlated to the variable of interest, for each element in the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] These data can be used to improve accuracy in sample design.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] One option is to use the auxiliary variable as a basis for stratification, as discussed above.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Another option is probability proportional to size ('PPS') sampling, in which the selection probability for each element is set to be proportional to its size measure, up to a maximum of 1.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In a simple PPS design, these selection probabilities can then be used as the basis for Poisson sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] However, this has the drawback of variable sample size, and different portions of the population may still be over- or under-represented due to chance variation in selections.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling theory can be used to create a probability proportionate to size sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This is done by treating each count within the size variable as a single sampling unit.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Samples are then identified by selecting at even intervals among these counts within the size variable.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This method is sometimes called PPS-sequential or monetary unit sampling in the case of audits or forensic sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The PPS approach can improve accuracy for a given sample size by concentrating sample on large elements that have the greatest impact on population estimates.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] PPS sampling is commonly used for surveys of businesses, where element size varies greatly and auxiliary information is often available – for instance, a survey attempting to measure the number of guest-nights spent in hotels might use each hotel's number of rooms as an auxiliary variable.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In some cases, an older measurement of the variable of interest can be used as an auxiliary variable when attempting to produce more current estimates.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sometimes it is more cost-effective to select respondents in groups ('clusters').
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sampling is often clustered by geography or by time periods (nearly all samples are in some sense 'clustered' in time – although this is rarely taken into account in the analysis).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For instance, if surveying households within a city, we might choose to select 100 city blocks and then interview every household within the selected blocks.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Clustering can reduce travel and administrative costs.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the example above, an interviewer can make a single trip to visit several households in one block, rather than having to drive to a different block for each household.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It also means that one does not need a sampling frame listing all elements in the target population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Instead, clusters can be chosen from a cluster-level frame, with an element-level frame created only for the selected clusters.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the example above, the sample only requires a block-level city map for initial selections, and then a household-level map of the 100 selected blocks, rather than a household-level map of the whole city.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling (also known as clustered sampling) generally increases the variability of sample estimates above that of simple random sampling, depending on how the clusters differ between one another as compared to the within-cluster variation.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For this reason, cluster sampling requires a larger sample than SRS to achieve the same level of accuracy – but cost savings from clustering might still make this a cheaper option.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling is commonly implemented as multistage sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This is a complex form of cluster sampling in which two or more levels of units are embedded one in the other.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The first stage consists of constructing the clusters that will be used to sample from.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In the second stage, a sample of primary units is randomly selected from each cluster (rather than using all units contained in all selected clusters).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In following stages, in each of those selected clusters, additional samples of units are selected, and so on.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] All ultimate units (individuals, for instance) selected at the last step of this procedure are then surveyed.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This technique, thus, is essentially the process of taking random subsamples of preceding random samples.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Multistage sampling can substantially reduce sampling costs, where the complete population list would need to be constructed (before other sampling methods could be applied).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] By eliminating the work involved in describing clusters that are not selected, multistage sampling can reduce the large costs associated with traditional cluster sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] However, each sample may not be a full representative of the whole population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In *quota sampling*, the population is first segmented into mutually exclusive sub-groups, just as in stratified sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Then judgement is used to select the subjects or units from each segment based on a specified proportion.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, an interviewer may be told to sample 200 females and 300 males between the age of 45 and 60.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is this second step which makes the technique one of nonprobability sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In quota sampling the selection of the sample is non-random.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, interviewers might be tempted to interview those who look most helpful.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The problem is that these samples may be biased because not everyone gets a chance of selection.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This random element is its greatest weakness and quota versus probability has been a matter of controversy for several years.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In imbalanced datasets, where the sampling ratio does not follow the population statistics, one can resample the dataset in a conservative manner called minimax sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The minimax sampling has its origin in Anderson minimax ratio whose value is proved to be 0.5: in a binary classification, the class-sample sizes should be chosen equally.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This ratio can be proved to be minimax ratio only under the assumption of LDA classifier with Gaussian distributions.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The notion of minimax sampling is recently developed for a general class of classification rules, called class-wise smart classifiers.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In this case, the sampling ratio of classes is selected so that the worst case classifier error over all the possible population statistics for class prior probabilities, would be the best.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Accidental sampling (sometimes known as **grab**, **convenience**, or **opportunity sampling**) is a type of nonprobability sampling which involves the sample being drawn from that part of the population which is close to hand.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] That is, a population is selected because it is readily available and convenient.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It may be through meeting the person or including a person in the sample when one meets them or chosen by finding them through technological means such as the internet or through phone.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The researcher using such a sample cannot scientifically make generalizations about the total population from this sample because it would not be representative enough.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This type of sampling is most useful for pilot testing.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Is there good reason to believe that a particular convenience sample would or should respond or behave differently than a random sample from the same population?
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Is the question being asked by the research one that can adequately be answered using a convenience sample?
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In social science research, snowball sampling is a similar technique, where existing study subjects are used to recruit more subjects into the sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Some variants of snowball sampling, such as respondent driven sampling, allow calculation of selection probabilities and are probability sampling methods under certain conditions.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The voluntary sampling method is a type of nonprobability sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Volunteers may be invited through advertisements in social media.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The target population for advertisements can be selected by characteristics like location, age, sex, income, occupation, education, or interests using tools provided by the social medium.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The advertisement may include a message about the research and link to a survey.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] After following the link and completing the survey, the volunteer submits the data to be included in the sample population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This method can reach a global population but is limited by the campaign budget.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Volunteers outside the invited population may also be included in the sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is difficult to make generalizations from this sample because it may not represent the total population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Often, volunteers have a strong interest in the main topic of the survey.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Line-intercept sampling is a method of sampling elements in a region whereby an element is sampled if a chosen line segment, called a "transect", intersects the element.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Snowball sampling involves finding a small group of initial respondents and using them to recruit more respondents.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is particularly useful in cases where the population is hidden or difficult to enumerate.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Theoretical sampling occurs when samples are selected on the basis of the results of the data collected so far with a goal of developing a deeper understanding of the area or develop theories.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] An initial, general sample is first collected with the goal of investigating general trends, where further sampling may consist of extreme or very specific cases might be selected in order to maximize the likelihood a phenomenon will actually be observable.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In active sampling, the samples which are used for training a machine learning algorithm are actively selected, also compare active learning (machine learning).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Judgement sampling, also known as expert or purposive sampling, is a type of non-random sampling where samples are selected based on the opinion of an expert, who can select participants based on how valuable the information they provide is.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling refers to the idea of using human judgement to simulate randomness.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Despite samples being hand-picked, the goal is to ensure that no conscious bias exists within the choice of samples, but often fails due to selection bias.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling is generally opted for due to its convenience, when the tools or capacity to perform other sampling methods may not exist.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The major weakness of such samples is that they often do not represent the characteristics of the entire population, but just a segment of the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Because of this unbalanced representation, results from haphazard sampling are often biased.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sampling schemes may be *without replacement* ('WOR' – no element can be selected more than once in the same sample) or *with replacement* ('WR' – an element may appear multiple times in the one sample).
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, if we catch fish, measure them, and immediately return them to the water before continuing with the sample, this is a WR design, because we might end up catching and measuring the same fish more than once.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] However, if we do not return the fish to the water or tag and release each fish after catching it, this becomes a WOR design.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Formulas, tables, and power function charts are well known approaches to determine sample size.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Locate the column corresponding to the estimated effect size.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The intersection of the column and row is the minimum sample size required.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For example, there are about 600 million tweets produced every day.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] It is not necessary to look at all of them to determine the topics that are discussed during the day, nor is it necessary to look at all the tweets to determine the sentiment on each of the topics.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A theoretical formulation for sampling Twitter data has been developed.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] To predict down-time it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Survey results are typically subject to some error.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Total errors can be classified into sampling errors and non-sampling errors.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The term "error" here includes systematic biases as well as random errors.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Sampling errors and biases are induced by the sample design.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Random sampling error: Random variation in the results due to the elements in the sample being selected at random.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Non-sampling errors are other errors which can impact final survey estimates, caused by problems in data collection, processing, or sample design.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Under-coverage: sampling frame does not include elements in the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] After sampling, a review is held of the exact process followed in sampling, rather than that intended, in order to study any effects that any divergences might have on subsequent analysis.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A particular problem involves *non-response*.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, many of the individuals identified as part of the sample may be unwilling to participate, not have the time to participate (opportunity cost), or survey administrators may not have been able to contact them.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In this case, there is a risk of differences between respondents and nonrespondents, leading to biased estimates of population parameters.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This is often addressed by improving survey design, offering incentives, and conducting follow-up studies which make a repeated attempt to contact the unresponsive and to characterize their similarities and differences with the rest of the frame.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The effects can also be mitigated by weighting the data (when population benchmarks are available) or by imputing data based on answers to other questions.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Nonresponse is particularly a problem in internet sampling.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Reasons for this problem may include improperly designed surveys, over-surveying (or survey fatigue), and the fact that potential participants may have multiple e-mail addresses, which they do not use anymore or do not check regularly.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] In many situations, the sample fraction may be varied by stratum and data will have to be weighted to correctly represent the population.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Thus for example, a simple random sample of individuals in the United Kingdom might not include some in remote Scottish islands who would be inordinately expensive to sample.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] A cheaper method would be to use a stratified sample with urban and rural strata.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] The rural sample could be under-represented in the sample, but weighted up appropriately in the analysis to compensate.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] More generally, data should usually be weighted if the sample design does not give each individual an equal chance of being selected.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] For instance, when households have equal selection probabilities but one person is interviewed from within each household, this gives people from large households a smaller chance of being interviewed.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] This can be accounted for using survey weights.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Similarly, households with more than one telephone line have a greater chance of being selected in a random digit dialing sample, and weights can adjust for this.
[src:autoregressive-models/sampling-statistics] Weights can also serve other purposes, such as helping to correct for non-response.
